---
description: Git conventions — commit messages, branch naming, PR/MR standards, merge strategy, and what never to commit.
alwaysApply: true
---

# Commit Messages
- Follow Conventional Commits format: `<type>(<scope>): <description>`
- Types: `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `test`, `chore`, `docs`, `ci`, `perf`
- Description: lowercase, imperative mood, no period at the end:
```
  # good
  feat(auth): add JWT refresh token support
  fix(user): handle missing email in registration flow
  refactor(orders): extract payment logic into service layer

  # bad
  Fixed bug
  WIP
  changes
```
- Keep subject line under 72 characters.
- Add body when the "why" is not obvious — explain context, not what changed.

# Branch Naming
- Pattern: `<type>/<short-description>` or `<type>/<ticket-id>-<short-description>`
```
  feat/user-authentication
  fix/PROJ-123-null-pointer-on-login
  refactor/extract-payment-service
  chore/upgrade-dependencies
```
- Use `kebab-case` — no spaces, no underscores.
- Keep branch names short and descriptive.

# PR / MR Standards
- Title follows the same Conventional Commits format as commit messages.
- Description must include: what changed, why, and how to test it.
- Keep PRs small and focused — one concern per PR.
- Link to the relevant ticket/issue.
- Never merge your own PR — always require at least one reviewer.
- Resolve all comments before merging.

# Merge Strategy
- Use **squash merge** for feature branches → keeps main history clean.
- Use **merge commit** for release branches → preserves release history.
- Never force push to `main` or `master`.
- Delete branches after merging.

# What Never to Commit
- Secrets, API keys, tokens, passwords — use `.env` (always in `.gitignore`)
- Generated files — `__pycache__/`, `*.pyc`, `.venv/`, `dist/`, `build/`
- IDE config — `.idea/`, `.vscode/` (unless team-agreed)
- Large binary files — use Git LFS if unavoidable
- Temporary files — `*.tmp`, `*.log`

# General Rules
- Never commit directly to `main` or `master` — always use a branch + PR.
- Commit early and often — small, focused commits are easier to review and revert.
- Every commit must leave the codebase in a working state.
- If you need to revert, use `git revert` — never `git reset` on shared branches.
